It looks like there is a simultaneous write off of large non essential assets while share price is low across the majors and kind of nobody notices in a market still under shock. Maybe that added to the ease of the of production control, but still a bit fuzzy for me.

7/31/20: CVX shares fall after Q2 loss, limited upside from here. uncertain outlook from management and cautious sell side commentary makes me give more weight to buckets less than spot, currently at $83.40.
Closed at 86.27 today. Trading between 82.74 and 91.39 for the last month.
Mr. Market can be volitile. What a difference a little earnings report can make.
Current closing price is $90.07. Estimates are pointing to no surprises in the quarterly earnings [1].
The current price is meandering between 85-95 dollars and trending downward slightly. However, it has only gone above 100 once since the pandemic started and hasn't dipped below 75 since April 1st.

Significant reductions in supply make it unlikely the price will drop below $83.00. This is especially the case now that the likelihood of a dividend cut is less following the Noble acquisition. This prediction assumes a slight sell off from current levels following earnings and additional news of schools going virtual for the Fall.
July 27= 90.73USD matching the increase in the price of WTI.

Slowly, but steadily appears to be growing back to pre-COVID values and new travel data shows that nationwide, Americans are taking more long trips than they were before the pandemic struck (https://www.cnn.com/travel/article/summer-road-trips-coronavirus-spike/index.html).
Reverse implied stock probabiliteis from spot and IV. Will have to keep a close eye on earnings release, slated for 7/31 pre market.

On Jul 26, the price was $90.13. Chevron earnings will be released on Jul 31, which seems to be the main factor to affect price movement. The Chevron earnings Q1 2020 strongly beat people's expectation, but Q2 also seems a tough quarter for Chevron, so now my guess is slightly negative.
It is at $90 now but earnings are announced July 31. Experts say it will lose money. Shares likely to dip for a bit. How far?

I don't see a lot of evidence that large fluctuations in the stock price correlate with quarterly earning reports. I guess this year might be a bit different, as the report might reveal some larger issues caused by the corona crisis?
Snapping back to trend. The good news is yesterday's news.
July 23 = 90.43USD in a down market. Touched above 91 during the day. What a Nobel thing to do.
The stock has risen to over $91.36 on the, perhaps surprise, announcement of Chevron's purchase of Noble Energy today.

I should've updated this sooner. Excluding an arbitrary dip or additional Trump slumps, Chevron seems to me priced as a steal and making moves: recent news: https://www.forbes.com/sites/davidblackmon/2020/07/20/chevrons-deal-to-buy-noble-energy-attracts-positive-analyst-reviews/#fe1297b2459a

I don't have too much information on analyzing the Chevron company, so it is difficult to express any alpha outside of the market view. However, I can analyze call option deltas near the Aug5th strike to gauge what probability distribution the market is pricing in. These greeks tell me approximately the probability of the option being in the money, which I will set as my prior.

CVX will protect its dividend and has the cash management to do so. There will be buying pressure as the rate approaches 7%
Dark days of April saw 68. Heady days of early June saw 103 (before reality of reopening set in). We are wiser now and realize we are not out of the woods.

Three days into the first week of the month. Lots of economic reports will be floating around. Earning season starts now with the banks and everything about the 2nd Q will look as bad as anytime in the past. Energy demand may be down and the Saudis may be trying to discipline a hard to control OPEC. I can not think of the positive reason needed to see an increase in the share price. Short of Warren Buffet adding it to his energy portfolio I do not see any higher price on this stock.
Airline use will continue to decline with increasing Covid-19 cases around the globe. Vehicle use will not make up for the lost jet fuel revenue.
Going with the crowd, except putting some chips on the $91-99 space. It's a small bet that CVX will revert towards its mean value of the past 3 months.
